<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2000b, &ldquo;Review of Anthony Ashley
Cooper, Third Earl of Shaftesbury, <em>Characteristicks of Men,
Manners, Opinions, Times</em>, Philip Ayres (ed.),&rdquo; <em>Review
of English Studies</em>, 51: 617&ndash;21.</li>

<li>Ryan, Robert M., 1977, &ldquo;Keats&rsquo;s &lsquo;Hymn to
Pan&rsquo;: A Debt to Shaftesbury?,&rdquo; <em>Keats-Shelley
Journal</em>, 26: 31&ndash;34.</li>

<li>Savile, Anthony, 2002, &ldquo;Aesthetic Experience in
Shaftesbury,&rdquo; <em>Proceedings of the Aristotelian Society</em>
(Supplementary Volume), 76: 55&ndash;74.</li>

<li>Schneewind, J.B., 1998, <em>The Invention of Autonomy</em>,
Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>Sellars, John, 2016, &ldquo;Shaftesbury, Stoicism, and Philosophy
as a Way of Life,&rdquo; <em>Sophia</em>, 55: 395&ndash;408.</li>

<li>Sidgwick, Henry, 1902, <em>Outlines of the History of Ethics</em>,
London: Macmillan.</li>

<li>Solomon, Harry M., 1975, &ldquo;Shaftesbury&rsquo;s
<em>Characteristics</em> and the Conclusion of &lsquo;Ode on a Grecian
Urn,&rsquo;&rdquo; <em>Keats-Shelly Journal</em>, 24:
89&ndash;101.</li>

<li>Spellman, William M., 1988, <em>John Locke and the Problem of
Depravity</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Stolnitz, Jerome, 1961a, &ldquo;On the Significance of Lord
Shaftesbury in Modern Aesthetic Theory,&rdquo; <em>Philosophical
Quarterly</em>, 43: 97&ndash;113.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1961b, &ldquo;&lsquo;Beauty&rsquo;: Some
Stages in the History of an Idea,&rdquo; <em>Journal of the History of
Ideas</em>, 22: 185&ndash;204.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1961c, &ldquo;On the Origins of
&lsquo;Aesthetic Disinterestedness,&rsquo;&rdquo; <em>Journal of
Aesthetics and Art Criticism</em>, 20: 131&ndash;43.</li>

<li>Storrie, Stefan, 2025, &ldquo;The Aptly named
&lsquo;Cratylus&rsquo;? Berkeley&rsquo;s Approach to Shaftesbury in
<em>Alciphron</em> III,&rdquo; <em>Journal of Modern Philosophy</em>,
7. doi:10.25894/jmp.2440</li>

<li>Stuart-Buttle, Tim, 2019, <em>From Moral Theology to Moral
Philosophy: Cicero and Visions of Humanity from Locke to Hume</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Taylor, C., 1989, <em>Sources of the Self: The Making of Modern
Identity</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>Thiel, U., 2011, <em>The Early Modern Subject: Self-Consciousness
and Person Identity from Descartes to Hume</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press.</li>

<li>Tierney-Hynes, Rebecca, 2005, &ldquo;Shaftesbury&rsquo;s
Soliloquy: Authorship and the Psychology of Romance,&rdquo;
<em>Eighteenth Century Studies</em>, 38(4): 605&ndash;621.</li>

<li>Tiffany, Esther A, 1923, &ldquo;Shaftesbury as Stoic,&rdquo;
<em>Publications of the Modern Languages Association</em>, 38(3):
642&ndash;685.</li>

<li>Townsend, Dabney, 1982, &ldquo;Shaftesbury&rsquo;s Aesthetic
Theory,&rdquo; <em>Journal of Aesthetics and Art Criticism</em>, 41:
205&ndash;13.</li>

<li>Trianosky, Gregory W., 1978, &ldquo;On the Obligation to be
Virtuous: Shaftesbury and the Question, Why be Moral?&rdquo;
<em>Journal of the History of Philosophy</em>, 16: 289&ndash;300.</li>

<li>Trumbach, Randolph, 1998, <em>Sex and the Gender Revolution,
volume 1: Heterosexuality and the Third Gender in Enlightenment
London</em>, Chicago: University of Chicago Press.</li>

<li>Tuveson, Ernest, 1948, &ldquo;The Origins of the &lsquo;Moral
Sense&rsquo;,&rdquo; <em>Huntington Library Quarterly</em>, 11:
241&ndash;59.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1960, <em>The Imagination as a Means of
Grace: Locke and the Aesthetics of Romanticism</em>, Berkeley:
University of California Press.</li>

<li>Uehlein, Friedrich A., 2017, &ldquo;Whichcote, Shaftesbury and
Locke: Shaftesbury&rsquo;s Critique of Locke&rsquo;s Epistemology and
Moral Philosophy,&rdquo; <em>British Journal for the History of
Philosophy</em>, 25(5): 1031&ndash;1048.</li>

<li>Voitle, Robert B., 1984, <em>The Third Earl of Shaftesbury,
1671&ndash;1713</em>, Baton Rouge and London: Louisiana State
University Press.</li>

<li>White, David, 1973, &ldquo;The Metaphysics of Disinterestedness:
Shaftesbury and Kant,&rdquo; <em>Journal of Aesthetics and Art
Criticism</em>, 32(2): 239&ndash;248.</li>

<li>Wiley, Basil, 1940, <em>The Eighteenth Century Background</em>,
New York: Columbia University Press.</li>

<li>Williams, Abigail, 2005, <em>Poetry and the Creation of a Whig
Literary Culture 1681&ndash;1714</em>, Oxford: Oxford University
Press.</li>

<li>Winkler, Kenneth P., 2000, &ldquo;&lsquo;All is Revolution in
Us&rsquo;: Personal Identity in Shaftesbury and Hume,&rdquo; <em>Hume
Studies</em>, 26: 3&ndash;40.</li>

<li>Woldt, Isabella, &ldquo;<em>Hercules at the Crossroads</em>:
Shaftesbury&rsquo;s Concept of Freedom, Neuroscience, and
Compatibilism,&rdquo; in <em>New Ages, New Opinions: Shaftesbury in
his World and Today</em>, Patrick M&uuml;ller (ed.), Frankfurt: Peter
Lang, 131&ndash;152.</li>
</ul>
</div> 

